<span style="font-weight: bold">Project: </span> <br />Create an animated looping scene as a background to a webpage with a similar effect to Rift: <a href="http://www.riftgame.com/en/" class="postlink">http://www.riftgame.com/en/</a> or Diablo3: <a href="http://us.blizzard.com/diablo3/" class="postlink">http://us.blizzard.com/diablo3/</a>.<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold">Goal:</span><br />Find an alternative to flash<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold">Idea:</span><br />Use HTML5's video tag along with the loop parameter to display the background.  Video tag works wonderfully with z-index so it isn't a problem except...<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold">Problem:</span><br />Firefox doesn't support the loop parameter<br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: </dt><dd><code>&lt;video loop=&quot;loop&gt;<br /></code></dd></dl><br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold">Solutions?:</span><br /><ul>1) Make people download a firefox plugin to allow looping.  Never in my right mind!<br />2) Use browser detect scripts and disable video tag just for firefox just to display flash, then fallback to static image.<br />3) Use flash with fallback to static image<br /></ul><br /><span style="font-weight: bold">Call for help:</span><br />Does anybody have any ideas to make this happen without resorting to flash?  Maybe embedding a movie into &lt;canvas&gt;?  or something?  If there isn't a solution I am fine doing flash, but just wanted to try something plugin independent.  Any comments on this would be very insightful.  Thanks.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=1846">Xacto01</a> — Thu Mar 24, 2011 9:14 pm</p><hr />
